  "prompt": "Is it unsafe to eat shrimp or fish that has been left out on the counter overnight then refrigerated? Twice?",
  "response": "Yes, it is generally unsafe to eat shrimp or fish that has been left out on the counter overnight, even if it was later refrigerated. Seafood can quickly reach temperatures where bacteria, such as Salmonella and Listeria, can grow. The USDA recommends not leaving perishable foods, including seafood, at room temperature for more than 2 hours, or 1 hour if the room temperature is above 90\u00b0F (32\u00b0C). \n\nLeaving shrimp or fish out overnight on the counter would likely ensure that it has been in the \"danger zone\" for bacterial growth (40\u00b0F - 140\u00b0F or 4\u00b0C - 60\u00b0C) for too long. Re-refrigerating it does not make it safe to eat as the potential bacteria could have multiplied to unsafe levels and may produce toxins that are not destroyed by cooking.\n\nTherefore, it would be best to discard the shrimp or fish to avoid the risk of foodborne illness.",
